text: .@deanbain1 No idea when I'll get to return to space. Many talented astros ahead of me training/waiting their turn. Back of the line for me
.@JumboPerli Every crew trained to sew up wounds, perform dental extractions, relieve abscesses, etc. Plus can stabilize trauma emergency.
.@MasonHeine Ran:bungeed to a treadmill. Cycled:on a stationary bike.Pushed & pulled: against vacuum pistons. Gained lean mass - it worked!
Back in Star City, Russia for debriefs. Good to see colleagues again that taught us how to fly the Soyuz.  Seems like yesterday...
.@DemianHaki Space surgery is hardware intensive + need the skills on-board. Today, if can't wait, can't treat medically, then must return.
Perfect morning under gray skies with a light rain & warm wind on my face. I missed life under clouds while in space.
.@JohnRSports @carolemcminn @csa_asc @esa We enjoyed new lo-salt foods on ISS, introduced for a variety of health reasons (incl. bone loss)!
.@digi_ben We have medical kits on ISS, specialists on ground for consultation, and the Soyuz as ambulance for the worst-case.
.@CaroleMcMinn @csa_asc Lots of research studying bone loss in astronauts -if we can cure it for space, we could cure it for all on Earth!
.@anna_walseth @britishgamer117 Bone loss in space is painless. Definitely some muscle aches in the legs and feet adapting to 1-g though!
.@britishgamer117 Lost a little bone mineral density in the hips, as expected. Bones dissolve in 0-g, exercise builds them back!
My nemesis-the cones. First just stepping over them, then running around them working on speed and agility. http://t.co/eI5YLI2XEN
This weekend enjoyed my first unscripted day since launch last year.  Worked in the yard - exactly what I looked forward to while in space!
.@Anorak_Al @psutympany Russian suit is 4 Soyuz only - limited movement. EVA suits r little spaceships w/ joints so we can work outside.
Beautiful launch of S35!  Kazakh steppe over 100 deg warmer than during our launch over 5 months ago. Docking in just a few hours!
Watch @astro_luca @AstroKarenN launch today to start their journey on the ISS! Lift-off 16:31 Eastern Time! Follow on nasa.tv
.@psutympany The difference-our suits provide cushion, our custom seats tightly cradle us, & seats have throw room to spread out the impact.
.@jasonatharvard @colev15 @cmdr_hadfield @killerkadooogen Yes! Diffuse pink glow, then white-hot pieces of shielding flashing past.
.@ColeV15 @cmdr_hadfield @killerkadooogen Loud bang of decel jets & ground impact like a rear-end car crash, then we tipped over and rolled.
.@bkastevens I was allowed home 2 days after landing. Flight docs say when we can drive and then fly again. Not yet but making progress!
Finishing up lots of medical tests today: Hearing, vision, heart, spine, bone, muscle strength, psych. Part of reintroduction to Earth.
.@boblower1 If I pass my medicals then I get back in line and hope for reassignment. Back of the line though!

.@SailTheTethys @csa_asc  Gravity feels very strange for a few days, then mind and muscle remember it and begin to adapt. Still a workout!
Looking at the night sky from my backyard, can't believe a week ago I was in orbit.EVA partner Chris Cassidy is still up there at the helm.
.@LAismylady @cmdr_hadfield. Oppressive 4gs, whipping & spinning under chute, & detonating impact of landing. Best ride of our lives.
.@TraMaAstro 1st day on Earth gravity is a magnet that pulls on face, arms, legs, everything.Can even feel the tug between muscle and bone.
Feeling great, but foot muscles a little stiff after 5 months of floating.  ECGs, blood draws, MRIs, and more await....
